## Flattening Multilevel Lists & Skip Lists Concepts

A multilevel doubly linked list has nodes that may have a `child` pointer to another doubly linked list. Flattening means merging all levels into a single-level doubly linked list where all nodes appear in depth-first order. This is essentially DFS on a linked structure.

The iterative approach: when you encounter a node with a child, (1) find the tail of the child list, (2) connect the tail to `node.next`, (3) connect `node.next` to `child`, (4) set `child` to null, then continue iterating. This in-place approach runs in O(n) time and O(1) space (excluding the recursion stack of a recursive version).

A **skip list** is an advanced probabilistic data structure built on top of a sorted linked list, with multiple "express lane" layers for O(log n) average search, insert, and delete. While rarely implemented in interviews, it's a common system design topic — Redis uses skip lists for its sorted sets because they support efficient range queries and are simpler to implement than balanced BSTs.

### Python Example
```python
class Node:
    def __init__(self, val, prev=None, next=None, child=None):
        self.val = val
        self.prev = prev
        self.next = next
        self.child = child

def flatten(head: Node) -> Node:
    if not head:
        return None
    curr = head
    while curr:
        if curr.child:
            child = curr.child
            next_node = curr.next
            # Find tail of child list
            tail = child
            while tail.next:
                tail = tail.next
            # Connect curr -> child
            curr.next = child
            child.prev = curr
            curr.child = None
            # Connect tail -> next_node
            tail.next = next_node
            if next_node:
                next_node.prev = tail
        curr = curr.next
    return head

def flatten_recursive(head: Node) -> Node:
    if not head:
        return None
    if head.child:
        child_tail = flatten_recursive(head.child)
        child_head = head.child
        rest = head.next
        head.next = child_head
        child_head.prev = head
        head.child = None
        child_tail.next = rest
        if rest:
            rest.prev = child_tail
    if head.next:
        flatten_recursive(head.next)
    return head

# Skip List search (conceptual)
class SkipList:
    def search(self, target: int) -> bool:
        curr = self.head  # Start at top-left sentinel
        for level in reversed(range(self.max_level)):
            while curr.next[level] and curr.next[level].val < target:
                curr = curr.next[level]  # Move right
        curr = curr.next[0]  # Drop to bottom level
        return curr is not None and curr.val == target
```

### Java Example
```java
public Node flatten(Node head) {
    Node curr = head;
    while (curr != null) {
        if (curr.child != null) {
            Node child = curr.child;
            Node next = curr.next;
            Node tail = child;
            while (tail.next != null) tail = tail.next;
            curr.next = child; child.prev = curr; curr.child = null;
            tail.next = next; if (next != null) next.prev = tail;
        }
        curr = curr.next;
    }
    return head;
}
```

### Complexity Analysis
- **Flatten (iterative)**: O(n) time, O(1) space where n = total nodes across all levels
- **Flatten (recursive)**: O(n) time, O(d) space where d = depth of nesting
- **Skip list search**: O(log n) average, O(n) worst case
- **Skip list insert/delete**: O(log n) average

### Common Interview Questions
- LeetCode 430 — Flatten a Multilevel Doubly Linked List
- LeetCode 1206 — Design Skiplist
- LeetCode 716 — Max Stack (uses doubly linked list + map)

**Interview Tip:** The flatten problem tests your ability to manipulate multiple pointer connections simultaneously. Write out the four pointer assignments before coding: `curr.next = child`, `child.prev = curr`, `tail.next = next`, `next.prev = tail`. Doing this systematically prevents missing a pointer.

